We just need to have a
better idea about how

00:28:09.220 --> 00:28:10.961
to fix it and restore
responsibility

00:28:10.961 --> 00:28:13.210
rather than in their case,
just blow it up and do away

00:28:13.210 --> 00:28:14.510
with government.

00:28:14.510 --> 00:28:16.890
AUDIENCE: And I
guess the examples

00:28:16.890 --> 00:28:20.252
that you gave in the beginning
are illustrative of that.

00:28:20.252 --> 00:28:21.710
And it's a way that
we can actually

00:28:21.710 --> 00:28:25.470
use media and other things
to turn this problem around.

00:28:25.470 --> 00:28:28.220
Whenever there's a case of
someone drowning because

00:28:28.220 --> 00:28:31.180
of some regulation, this
should be what's on the news

00:28:31.180 --> 00:28:33.857
rather than making more
laws about other things.

00:28:33.857 --> 00:28:34.690
PHILIP HOWARD: Yeah.

00:28:34.690 --> 00:28:36.905
So just on that point,
every time there's a crisis,

00:28:36.905 --> 00:28:40.650
there will be a natural instinct
to say, why isn't there a law?

00:28:40.650 --> 00:28:42.070
And they'll pass a law.

00:28:42.070 --> 00:28:44.490
And often that's very
hard to overcome.

00:28:44.490 --> 00:28:45.970
It's just overwhelming.

00:28:45.970 --> 00:28:47.720
That's just going to
be the first reaction

00:28:47.720 --> 00:28:50.440
of any legislator.

00:28:50.440 --> 00:28:53.150
So what's needed
more than getting

00:28:53.150 --> 00:28:57.160
rid of that, which is probably
hard to do in all cases,

00:28:57.160 --> 00:29:00.330
is a year later, the
process by which you then

00:29:00.330 --> 00:29:01.620
take away the law.

00:29:01.620 --> 00:29:06.760
And you say it's not working
or it's counterproductive.

00:29:06.760 --> 00:29:09.404
Again, we don't have
that discussion.

00:29:09.404 --> 00:29:11.310
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:29:11.310 --> 00:29:14.330
So you mentioned earlier
that tech is just

00:29:14.330 --> 00:29:16.660
now starting to feel the pain.

00:29:16.660 --> 00:29:21.430
So one example was as you
know, Google sent five people

00:29:21.430 --> 00:29:24.390
to go help fix the
healthcare.gov website.

00:29:24.390 --> 00:29:27.120
And I feel like anyone who's
ever worked with government

00:29:27.120 --> 00:29:31.830
contracts know there's this
huge pile of paperwork that

00:29:31.830 --> 00:29:34.960
let's the government decide
how to pick contracts.

00:29:34.960 --> 00:29:36.180
And it's very bloated.

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:40.320
And I think healthcare.gov
had 20 different vendors that

00:29:40.320 --> 00:29:42.760
were hired just to
build one website.

00:29:42.760 --> 00:29:45.560
Have you done any
work with that space

00:29:45.560 --> 00:29:49.430
as far as reform or less rules
on who the government can

00:29:49.430 --> 00:29:51.690
hire to build something
like a website?

00:29:51.690 --> 00:29:56.330
That's been done multiple
times in the Bay Area.

00:29:56.330 --> 00:29:58.290
PHILIP HOWARD: They're
called procurement laws.

00:29:58.290 --> 00:30:00.655
And I was an adviser to
Al Gore and Bill Clinton

00:30:00.655 --> 00:30:04.880
in redoing the procurement laws
and the reinventing government

00:30:04.880 --> 00:30:06.560
campaign of 20 years ago.

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:07.760
So I worked very closely.

00:30:07.760 --> 00:30:09.436
I gave speeches, [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:14.260 --> 00:30:15.960
And they made a
few improvements,

00:30:15.960 --> 00:30:17.820
including, for
example, not having

00:30:17.820 --> 00:30:19.790
to go through those
idiotic processes

00:30:19.790 --> 00:30:22.070
when you want to go
buy a pad of paper.

00:30:24.670 --> 00:30:27.810
So they gave public employees
credit cards [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:27.810 --> 00:30:29.170
go buy office supplies.

00:30:29.170 --> 00:30:30.550
A minor reform.

00:30:30.550 --> 00:30:33.650
But believe it or not,
that was a reform.

00:30:33.650 --> 00:30:37.477
But they haven't fixed
it for big procurement.

00:30:37.477 --> 00:30:40.070
Things like healthcare.gov
and so forth.

00:30:43.580 --> 00:30:46.840
The government spends--
I forget the numbers--

00:30:46.840 --> 00:30:50.780
it's over $500 billion a year
in outside government contracts.

00:30:50.780 --> 00:30:54.370
Best estimates are they waste
between 30% and 40% of it

00:30:54.370 --> 00:30:56.780
through these procedures
that basically

00:30:56.780 --> 00:31:01.910
try to prescribed in advance how
the-- so they literally specify

00:31:01.910 --> 00:31:05.420
in advance how you're going
to create the website instead

00:31:05.420 --> 00:31:09.680
of letting smart engineers get
in a room, and work through

00:31:09.680 --> 00:31:13.190
and adapt to all the problems.

00:31:13.190 --> 00:31:17.020
It's a form of mental illness
to think that you can actually

00:31:17.020 --> 00:31:20.310
accomplish anything
by writing in advance

00:31:20.310 --> 00:31:22.457
and then saying just go do it.

00:31:22.457 --> 00:31:24.540
I happened to be on the
plane last night out there

00:31:24.540 --> 00:31:26.690
with the head of a
division of Boeing.

00:31:26.690 --> 00:31:33.370
And we were discussing the
problems of procurement

00:31:33.370 --> 00:31:38.075
and why it's so hard to get
good products at a good price

00:31:38.075 --> 00:31:38.950
through this process.

00:31:38.950 --> 00:31:40.770
I have another friend,
a high school classmate,

00:31:40.770 --> 00:31:42.269
who's the deputy
head of procurement

00:31:42.269 --> 00:31:44.040
at the Department of Defense.

00:31:44.040 --> 00:31:47.190
He gives speeches to hundreds
of procurement officials,

00:31:47.190 --> 00:31:49.350
saying, please
use your judgment.

00:31:49.350 --> 00:31:51.220
Please be flexible.

00:31:51.220 --> 00:31:55.540
But you have this whole culture
of nobody using their judgment.

00:31:55.540 --> 00:31:59.860
That area truly needs
to get replaced.

00:31:59.860 --> 00:32:04.270
It needs to get replaced by
a system where you identify

00:32:04.270 --> 00:32:07.270
an official, that works
underneath him, that

00:32:07.270 --> 00:32:10.480
is in charge of letting the
contract because no one's going

00:32:10.480 --> 00:32:12.030
to trust him.

00:32:12.030 --> 00:32:14.865
You maybe have an industry
committee of people [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:14.865 --> 00:32:19.420
industries who have the
authority to review and reverse

00:32:19.420 --> 00:32:23.180
contracts, something like that.

00:32:23.180 --> 00:32:26.130
And it would happen in
the third of the time

00:32:26.130 --> 00:32:27.890
and save all that money.

00:32:27.890 --> 00:32:28.594
It's broken.

00:32:28.594 --> 00:32:30.802
There's not one government
program that isn't broken.

00:32:30.802 --> 00:32:33.030
Let's go there.

00:32:33.030 --> 00:32:37.675
The question's whether
it's broken 25% or 95%.

00:32:37.675 --> 00:32:42.115
That one's broken about 65%.

00:32:42.115 --> 00:32:43.597
Yes?

00:32:43.597 --> 00:32:45.680
AUDIENCE: For every rule
I think that's out there,

00:32:45.680 --> 00:32:48.100
if there isn't sort of a
vested minority interest

00:32:48.100 --> 00:32:50.516
that's keeping it alive, even
though it should be extinct,

00:32:50.516 --> 00:32:53.060
there might have been a
transgression at some point.

00:32:53.060 --> 00:32:55.323
So for example, where
in the nursing homes,

00:32:55.323 --> 00:32:58.684
you have to cook the eggs or the
food has to be above 35 inches,

00:32:58.684 --> 00:33:00.850
I imagine at some point,
someone did something wrong

00:33:00.850 --> 00:33:02.580
and it turned into a lawsuit.

00:33:02.580 --> 00:33:05.330
So I'm wondering to what extent
there has to be tort reform

00:33:05.330 --> 00:33:09.060
or the law needs to
change so that it's not

00:33:09.060 --> 00:33:11.760
such a lawyer, sue-happy
culture and so [INAUDIBLE]?

00:33:11.760 --> 00:33:15.160
PHILIP HOWARD: That's really,
really important point.

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:16.660
There's a general
instinct by people

00:33:16.660 --> 00:33:18.823
to avoid responsibility
in general.

00:33:18.823 --> 00:33:20.906
So if they have an excuse
to avoid responsibility,

00:33:20.906 --> 00:33:22.370
they will.

00:33:22.370 --> 00:33:24.843
It's like people
in Plato's cave.

00:33:24.843 --> 00:33:27.301
As long as you feed us, we're
happy to be down in the cave.

00:33:30.910 --> 00:33:32.560
The fear of litigation.

00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:35.910
What the fire chief in
Alameda County said,

00:33:35.910 --> 00:33:38.380
[INAUDIBLE], I can't
go in the ocean.

00:33:38.380 --> 00:33:41.640
There might be liability.

00:33:41.640 --> 00:33:42.570
Liability to who?

00:33:42.570 --> 00:33:44.709
For saving a life?

00:33:44.709 --> 00:33:46.250
You think about it
for one nanosecond

00:33:46.250 --> 00:33:49.560
and you think, well, that's
the dumbest thing you've ever.

00:33:49.560 --> 00:33:52.010
But he said it.

00:33:52.010 --> 00:33:54.880
So there is this kind
of abstract fear,

00:33:54.880 --> 00:33:57.410
which I have
written a lot about.

00:33:57.410 --> 00:34:00.470
The problem with the system of
civil justice in this country

00:34:00.470 --> 00:34:02.580
isn't that juries are
so stupid or whatever.

00:34:02.580 --> 00:34:05.070
It's that now waves
of defensiveness

00:34:05.070 --> 00:34:08.949
have overcome all of society.

00:34:08.949 --> 00:34:12.110
Teachers will no longer put
an arm around a crying child.

00:34:12.110 --> 00:34:14.300
My law firm has a
rule, as every business

00:34:14.300 --> 00:34:17.520
does-- I think Google
does too-- that you're not

00:34:17.520 --> 00:34:20.874
allowed to give a job reference.

00:34:20.874 --> 00:34:22.364
It's so stupid.

00:34:22.364 --> 00:34:24.030
This is the land of
the First Amendment.

00:34:24.030 --> 00:34:25.120
You're not allowed to
give a job reference?

00:34:25.120 --> 00:34:26.530
You get scared
you might get sued

00:34:26.530 --> 00:34:30.520
if you say some
qualifying fact that's

00:34:30.520 --> 00:34:33.120
honest about an employee?

00:34:33.120 --> 00:34:34.130
So yes, we do.

00:34:34.130 --> 00:34:38.794
And I talk about
this in the book.

00:34:38.794 --> 00:34:40.530
At the end of the
book, I have a bill

00:34:40.530 --> 00:34:44.384
of responsibilities
that basically clarifies

00:34:44.384 --> 00:34:48.790
the responsibilities
of different branches

00:34:48.790 --> 00:34:49.840
of government.

00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:52.929
And with courts, I say
that basically no lawsuit

00:34:52.929 --> 00:34:56.110
should be allowed to
go forward until judge

00:34:56.110 --> 00:35:00.550
has made a legal ruling about
whether the claims should be

00:35:00.550 --> 00:35:02.470
allowed to go forward
and won't undermine

00:35:02.470 --> 00:35:05.079
the freedoms of other
people in the society.

00:35:05.079 --> 00:35:07.370
Because now we have this kind
of laissez-faire attitude

00:35:07.370 --> 00:35:08.470
of justice.

00:35:08.470 --> 00:35:10.110
Well, you've got a right to sue.

00:35:10.110 --> 00:35:12.470
People say that.

00:35:12.470 --> 00:35:14.360
Suing is not an act of freedom.

00:35:14.360 --> 00:35:15.995
Suing is an act of state power.

00:35:15.995 --> 00:35:19.080
Sue somebody, you win,
you take away their home.

00:35:19.080 --> 00:35:20.937
The sheriff comes and
takes away their home.

00:35:20.937 --> 00:35:23.145
We have, again, it's like
another one of these things

00:35:23.145 --> 00:35:27.220
where we've inverted
the role of law.

00:35:27.220 --> 00:35:29.600
So the whole point of lawsuits
is that they're lawsuits.

00:35:29.600 --> 00:35:33.200
Not like sue for
anything, [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:33.200 --> 00:35:37.854
So yeah, it's a really important
reform to go on [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:50.609 --> 00:35:51.150
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:35:51.150 --> 00:35:52.497
Thanks a lot for your talk. .

00:35:52.497 --> 00:35:54.080
I'm wondering how
much of this problem

00:35:54.080 --> 00:35:56.730
is the result of the
violation of the principle

00:35:56.730 --> 00:36:00.400
of subsidiarity, where
decisions and things ought

00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:02.160
to be made at the
lowest possible level.

00:36:02.160 --> 00:36:04.289
And the higher levels, like
the federal government,

00:36:04.289 --> 00:36:06.080
is getting involved in
things at the states

00:36:06.080 --> 00:36:06.760
ought to be handling.

00:36:06.760 --> 00:36:08.050
And the states are
getting involved in things

00:36:08.050 --> 00:36:10.362
that the local government
ought to be handling.

00:36:10.362 --> 00:36:12.070
PHILIP HOWARD: Really
important question.

00:36:12.070 --> 00:36:14.280
So there's a doctrine
that originated

00:36:14.280 --> 00:36:17.129
I think in the Catholic church
that responsibility should

00:36:17.129 --> 00:36:19.920
be pushed down to the
lowest possible level

00:36:19.920 --> 00:36:23.720
so that people on the
ground owned their choices.

00:36:23.720 --> 00:36:25.350
And since they own
their community,

00:36:25.350 --> 00:36:28.080
they own their schools
and such, rather

00:36:28.080 --> 00:36:30.935
than having top-down
bureaucracies rule

00:36:30.935 --> 00:36:34.320
to the ultimate centralization,
where in this case,

00:36:34.320 --> 00:36:36.520
dead people tell you what
to do because they wrote

00:36:36.520 --> 00:36:40.745
a rule 30 years ago [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:40.745 --> 00:36:43.240
And I talk about
subsidiarity in the book.

00:36:43.240 --> 00:36:45.960
So one of the solutions
here while you're

00:36:45.960 --> 00:36:50.960
doing the spring cleaning is to
the greatest extent possible,

00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:54.554
push down decisions
to a local level.

00:36:54.554 --> 00:36:56.220
That doesn't mean you
give up oversight.

00:36:56.220 --> 00:36:58.636
It doesn't mean people can do
whatever they want and teach

00:36:58.636 --> 00:37:03.960
creationism or whatever people
fear they're going to do.

00:37:03.960 --> 00:37:06.740
But the regulations
should be much lighter.

00:37:06.740 --> 00:37:10.050
Right now, you have
regulation, a rule of law.

00:37:10.050 --> 00:37:13.909
This big iron claw comes
down into everybody's lives,

00:37:13.909 --> 00:37:15.700
in their schools, and
in their communities.

00:37:15.700 --> 00:37:19.500
You need to lift up
that big iron claw.

00:37:19.500 --> 00:37:21.060
Let people do their own ways.

00:37:21.060 --> 00:37:26.230
And only get involved if people
really leave the reservation.

00:37:26.230 --> 00:37:28.000
They really leave the corral.

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:32.520
Again a really important
point because Americans

00:37:32.520 --> 00:37:35.726
no longer feel they
own their communities.

00:37:35.726 --> 00:37:37.890
And there are a lot
of studies of this.

00:37:37.890 --> 00:37:39.090
And the truth is they don't.

00:37:41.790 --> 00:37:45.130
If you're a retired physicist
or a retired software engineer

00:37:45.130 --> 00:37:50.380
and you want to go work
in the schools, you can't.

00:37:50.380 --> 00:37:53.312
You're much better qualified
than anybody in the school,

00:37:53.312 --> 00:37:55.020
but you're not certified
to be a teacher.

00:37:55.020 --> 00:37:56.590
Sorry.

00:37:56.590 --> 00:38:00.070
If you want to go help
in a hospice, you can't.

00:38:00.070 --> 00:38:02.744
Are you certified?

00:38:02.744 --> 00:38:04.160
All these bureaucratic
constraints

00:38:04.160 --> 00:38:06.730
prevent real people
who are qualified

00:38:06.730 --> 00:38:09.056
for getting involved
in their communities.

00:38:13.412 --> 00:38:14.380
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:14.380 --> 00:38:15.360
PHILIP HOWARD:
[INAUDIBLE] question here?

00:38:15.360 --> 00:38:16.280
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:38:16.280 --> 00:38:19.500
PHILIP HOWARD: We have one
more for the cameraman.

00:38:19.500 --> 00:38:21.970
[INAUDIBLE] this question.

00:38:21.970 --> 00:38:24.380
AUDIENCE: Well, I
actually was an educator.

00:38:24.380 --> 00:38:27.080
And you talked about education--
I was a special education

00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:28.020
teacher.

00:38:28.020 --> 00:38:30.364
And we got a significant
part of the budget.

00:38:30.364 --> 00:38:31.780
But the other thing
I seem to find

00:38:31.780 --> 00:38:34.790
is, is that more and more
students were then identified

00:38:34.790 --> 00:38:36.947
as being special needs students.

00:38:36.947 --> 00:38:39.030
And it seemed like there
was a significant portion

00:38:39.030 --> 00:38:42.380
of the community that felt
served by what some of us

00:38:42.380 --> 00:38:43.799
thought was a broken system.

00:38:43.799 --> 00:38:45.340
So how do you address
the people that

00:38:45.340 --> 00:38:47.402
feel served, even
though it's broken?

00:38:47.402 --> 00:38:49.360
PHILIP HOWARD: You have
to make common choices.

00:38:49.360 --> 00:38:52.540
Special ed, according to
some studies I've seen,

00:38:52.540 --> 00:38:55.027
has twice the number of people
than it ought to have in it.

00:38:55.027 --> 00:38:57.110
It becomes a place where
you get special training.

00:38:57.110 --> 00:38:59.360
You get more time
to take your test.

00:38:59.360 --> 00:39:00.940
There are all
kinds of advantages

00:39:00.940 --> 00:39:06.977
to being designated
into special ed.

00:39:06.977 --> 00:39:09.435
You can't run a democracy by
the lowest common denominator.

00:39:13.405 --> 00:39:18.600
You can't have environmental
reviews that last ten years.

00:39:18.600 --> 00:39:20.880
Germany, a much greener
country, [INAUDIBLE] last one,

00:39:20.880 --> 00:39:25.160
two years at the
most because they

00:39:25.160 --> 00:39:26.765
have a decision-maker
who says, OK.

00:39:26.765 --> 00:39:27.390
We [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:27.390 --> 00:39:28.723
Now we're going to have to this.

00:39:28.723 --> 00:39:30.734
This official has
a responsibility

00:39:30.734 --> 00:39:31.525
to make a decision.

00:39:31.525 --> 00:39:33.910
And that can be appealed to
that official and that's it.

00:39:37.110 --> 00:39:44.040
And the budget in schools is
a limited amount of dollars.

00:39:44.040 --> 00:39:46.915
I think we need
in inner cities--

00:39:46.915 --> 00:39:50.760
the experts I've talked to think
we need a dramatic redirection.

00:39:50.760 --> 00:39:54.670
Not to pre-K education,
but to prenatal education.

00:39:54.670 --> 00:39:57.060
Really getting these
kids and their mothers

00:39:57.060 --> 00:40:00.130
before they're born so they can
develop language skills and all

00:40:00.130 --> 00:40:03.754
the things that happen in
the first couple of years.

00:40:03.754 --> 00:40:05.191
That's expensive.

00:40:05.191 --> 00:40:07.890
Where does the money come from?

00:40:07.890 --> 00:40:10.850
So we have to make these
choices in our society.

00:40:10.850 --> 00:40:14.670
And if it's all preset in legal
concrete, we can't [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:14.670 --> 00:40:16.810
One more question.

00:40:16.810 --> 00:40:19.540
AUDIENCE: So I think served
is one aspect to people

00:40:19.540 --> 00:40:20.810
who feel served by the laws.

00:40:20.810 --> 00:40:22.520
But I think also
there's an aspect

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:24.700
of people being
scared by change.

00:40:24.700 --> 00:40:26.574
So the more we talk
about this, like

00:40:26.574 --> 00:40:27.990
you just mentioned
the physicists.

00:40:27.990 --> 00:40:31.310
So you excited all the
physicists in the room.

00:40:31.310 --> 00:40:34.200
But you just scared
millions of teachers

00:40:34.200 --> 00:40:37.400
because they are comfortable
with the current law.

00:40:37.400 --> 00:40:39.710
When you talk about
balancing the budget

00:40:39.710 --> 00:40:42.860
and you talk about the three
big programs, well, OK.

00:40:42.860 --> 00:40:45.260
So Social Security and Medicare.

00:40:45.260 --> 00:40:47.890
You just scared a whole
'nother group of people.

00:40:47.890 --> 00:40:48.950
And we can go on and on.

00:40:48.950 --> 00:40:52.370
The more we talk about this,
basically everyone in this room

00:40:52.370 --> 00:40:56.264
is going to be scared--
well, maybe not.

00:40:56.264 --> 00:40:58.430
The percentage of people
that are going to be scared

00:40:58.430 --> 00:41:03.580
is already about 50% just based
on the current conversation.

00:41:03.580 --> 00:41:05.360
PHILIP HOWARD:
And probably more.

00:41:05.360 --> 00:41:06.710
It's an excellent question.

00:41:06.710 --> 00:41:08.250
First of all, change is scary.

00:41:08.250 --> 00:41:09.804
Again, we go back
to Plato's cave.

00:41:09.804 --> 00:41:11.470
They didn't want to
go out in the light.

00:41:11.470 --> 00:41:14.770
They wanted to stay shackled
as much as they could.

00:41:14.770 --> 00:41:16.290
Just be where they are.

00:41:16.290 --> 00:41:18.190
So it's an evolutionary
imperative.

00:41:18.190 --> 00:41:19.750
We have food in our stomachs.

00:41:19.750 --> 00:41:23.110
People will never go
out to risk the world

00:41:23.110 --> 00:41:26.790
of saber-toothed tigers
and converging technology

00:41:26.790 --> 00:41:27.670
companies.

00:41:27.670 --> 00:41:28.503
This is [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:30.950 --> 00:41:32.980
So change is scary.

00:41:32.980 --> 00:41:35.500
But the status
quo is also scary.

00:41:35.500 --> 00:41:37.770
And so one of the
many things that's

00:41:37.770 --> 00:41:44.100
missing in our current
dialogue about our society

00:41:44.100 --> 00:41:47.000
are people who have
moral authority.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:51.130
So what's really important is
for people stand up and say not

00:41:51.130 --> 00:41:53.680
I'm going to get rid of
special ed the way it is,

00:41:53.680 --> 00:41:56.055
but to say we're going to
remake a whole bunch of things.

00:41:56.055 --> 00:41:58.950
And you're going to be
better off [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:58.950 --> 00:42:01.720
But everybody's going
to have to sacrifice.

00:42:01.720 --> 00:42:03.990
Because this huge
bureaucratic law,

00:42:03.990 --> 00:42:06.530
we're all feeding off of it.

00:42:06.530 --> 00:42:08.222
So we're scared to
lose the feeding off

00:42:08.222 --> 00:42:09.430
of this big bureaucratic law.

00:42:09.430 --> 00:42:11.970
But it's also suffocating us.

00:42:11.970 --> 00:42:14.799
And it's not sustainable
because we can't afford it.

00:42:14.799 --> 00:42:17.090
We're running half trillion
to trillion dollar deficits

00:42:17.090 --> 00:42:18.120
every year.

00:42:18.120 --> 00:42:21.010
We can't address climate change.

00:42:21.010 --> 00:42:23.130
We can't address immigration,
bad immigration law.

00:42:23.130 --> 00:42:24.315
We can't address anything.

00:42:26.890 --> 00:42:28.530
So how do you do that?

00:42:28.530 --> 00:42:32.278
Well, you need a group that
isn't vindictive and says,

00:42:32.278 --> 00:42:33.736
I'm going to get
you, which is sort

00:42:33.736 --> 00:42:36.130
of what both groups are about.

00:42:36.130 --> 00:42:38.820
You need people
with moral authority

00:42:38.820 --> 00:42:42.890
the people trust to be saying
what they really believe.

00:42:42.890 --> 00:42:46.350
You don't have to agree with it.

00:42:46.350 --> 00:42:53.400
And I challenge you to find
any public leader or even any

00:42:53.400 --> 00:42:58.500
public citizen-- maybe you can
find a couple [INAUDIBLE]--

00:42:58.500 --> 00:43:01.160
who have moral authority.

00:43:01.160 --> 00:43:04.280
Because the way we've organized
our dealings with government,

00:43:04.280 --> 00:43:08.650
even environmental groups
look like special interest.

00:43:08.650 --> 00:43:10.370
They just want to do that.

00:43:10.370 --> 00:43:12.582
They don't want to fix all
the other things to do.

00:43:12.582 --> 00:43:14.000
[INAUDIBLE].

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:17.150
So we need to pull back.

00:43:17.150 --> 00:43:19.010
This is a daunting problem.

00:43:19.010 --> 00:43:21.680
And there's a
wonderful anarchist

00:43:21.680 --> 00:43:23.195
called Peter Kropotkin.

00:43:23.195 --> 00:43:25.845
He wrote 100 years ago.

00:43:25.845 --> 00:43:26.865
He was a White Russian.

00:43:26.865 --> 00:43:29.347
Fled the revolution.

00:43:29.347 --> 00:43:31.430
Got a job writing for the
Encyclopedia Britannica.

00:43:31.430 --> 00:43:35.490
If it were now, he would be
working for Google for sure.

00:43:35.490 --> 00:43:38.270
Was a brilliant guy.

00:43:38.270 --> 00:43:40.990
Wrote these hysterical tracts.

00:43:40.990 --> 00:43:45.000
And he said, the more
miserable a man is,

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:49.255
the more he fears change lest it
make him more miserable still.

00:43:52.400 --> 00:43:56.790
And so we do have to fight
human nature in doing it.

00:43:56.790 --> 00:43:59.680
Everything I'm saying requires
fighting with human nature.

00:43:59.680 --> 00:44:01.280
That doesn't mean
that' it's right.

00:44:01.280 --> 00:44:04.080
It just means we
got to deal with it.

00:44:04.080 --> 00:44:06.360
Thank you.

